00:00:09.200 --> 00:00:12.240
You mentioned the various
types of accelerators

00:00:12.240 --> 00:00:15.996
such as the proton-proton,
proton-electron,

00:00:15.996 --> 00:00:17.790
electron-positron.

00:00:17.790 --> 00:00:19.430
What are the differences
between those?

00:00:19.430 --> 00:00:21.470
What will they do for you?

00:00:21.470 --> 00:00:24.510
Quite apart from the technology,
what does the proton-proton

00:00:24.510 --> 00:00:31.420
do for you as opposed to
electron-positron and so on?

00:00:31.420 --> 00:00:32.837
Yeah, would you
like to take that?

00:00:32.837 --> 00:00:33.336
Yeah.

00:00:33.336 --> 00:00:33.870
Yeah.

00:00:33.870 --> 00:00:36.940
OK, so is the mic on?

00:00:36.940 --> 00:00:38.410
Yeah, OK.

00:00:38.410 --> 00:00:41.450
I mean, in a way there isn't
really a dispute among those,

00:00:41.450 --> 00:00:43.230
I think, because the
different facilities

00:00:43.230 --> 00:00:45.480
that have been discussed
here have different pluses

00:00:45.480 --> 00:00:48.250
and minuses in terms
of their ability

00:00:48.250 --> 00:00:50.640
to attack new physics,
which is what we're really

00:00:50.640 --> 00:00:51.910
trying to get at.

00:00:51.910 --> 00:00:54.800
And so they're
complementary in many ways.

00:00:54.800 --> 00:00:57.150
So, as Frank
correctly said, it's

00:00:57.150 --> 00:01:00.280
easy to accelerate
protons compared

00:01:00.280 --> 00:01:02.930
with electrons or
positrons in a big ring

00:01:02.930 --> 00:01:04.440
because they don't
emit synchrotron

00:01:04.440 --> 00:01:06.564
radiation in the same way
because they're much more

00:01:06.564 --> 00:01:07.420
massive.

00:01:07.420 --> 00:01:09.790
The problem is-- so you
can get proton beams

00:01:09.790 --> 00:01:11.050
to very high energies.

00:01:11.050 --> 00:01:14.130
But when you slam
protons into one another,

00:01:14.130 --> 00:01:17.070
protons are not
elementary particles,

00:01:17.070 --> 00:01:20.080
they're bags of
quarks and gluons.

00:01:20.080 --> 00:01:22.400
And so a little
bit of one proton

00:01:22.400 --> 00:01:25.490
will hit a little
bit of another proton

00:01:25.490 --> 00:01:27.230
and they will scatter
from one another.

00:01:27.230 --> 00:01:30.200
So although you have a
very high beam energies,

00:01:30.200 --> 00:01:33.310
the energies of the
interacting particles

00:01:33.310 --> 00:01:36.890
typically are very much lower
than the maximum beam energy

00:01:36.890 --> 00:01:39.025
available because it's a
bit of one proton that's

00:01:39.025 --> 00:01:40.150
hitting a bit of the other.

00:01:40.150 --> 00:01:43.680
And then you have the rest of
the proton which causes a mess.

00:01:43.680 --> 00:01:45.340
So, in fact, the
center of mass energy

00:01:45.340 --> 00:01:47.410
of a proton-proton machine,
the effective center

00:01:47.410 --> 00:01:49.610
of mass energy, is not
as high as the beam

00:01:49.610 --> 00:01:51.010
energy written on the tin.

00:01:51.010 --> 00:01:52.680
It's roughly an
order of magnitude

00:01:52.680 --> 00:01:56.960
lower than the notional
twice the beam energies.

00:01:56.960 --> 00:01:58.630
And then you have a
lot of background,

00:01:58.630 --> 00:02:01.890
but you can get the beams to
really high energies using

00:02:01.890 --> 00:02:02.970
that technique.

00:02:02.970 --> 00:02:04.730
With electrons and
positrons there's

00:02:04.730 --> 00:02:06.940
a fundamental point
like particles.

00:02:06.940 --> 00:02:09.139
And so when an electron
and positron annihilate

00:02:09.139 --> 00:02:10.570
you just get the energy.

00:02:10.570 --> 00:02:12.950
That energy condenses
into the new things.

00:02:12.950 --> 00:02:14.900
You know everything
about the collisions

00:02:14.900 --> 00:02:16.780
because the momentum
is zero and you

00:02:16.780 --> 00:02:18.900
can measure the energies
of the beams coming in.

00:02:18.900 --> 00:02:21.690
And so you have complete
understanding of the kinematics

00:02:21.690 --> 00:02:22.990
of these interactions.

00:02:22.990 --> 00:02:26.180
And so when you make Higgs
particles, for example,

00:02:26.180 --> 00:02:29.250
there's the Higgs boson and the
zed boson in the final state

00:02:29.250 --> 00:02:30.240
and nothing else.

00:02:30.240 --> 00:02:32.290
So from an experimental
point of view,

00:02:32.290 --> 00:02:34.400
they're really quite
complementary ways

00:02:34.400 --> 00:02:35.841
of attacking the physics.

00:02:35.841 --> 00:02:38.090
And, of course, the physics
is the same for all of us.

00:02:38.090 --> 00:02:41.110
It's the physics of top
quarks, Higgs boson,

00:02:41.110 --> 00:02:45.220
dark matter, supersymmetry, or
whatever it may be out there.

00:02:45.220 --> 00:02:48.740
So is that a sort
of a first clue

00:02:48.740 --> 00:02:51.246
as to some of the differences
in what these things do,

00:02:51.246 --> 00:02:53.620
the pluses and minuses of all
these different techniques.

00:02:53.620 --> 00:02:55.460
So I sometimes say
with that as well

00:02:55.460 --> 00:02:57.190
that the hadron
machines are kind

00:02:57.190 --> 00:03:01.240
of discovery machines because
of that mix up of momentum.

00:03:01.240 --> 00:03:03.420
You can get all kinds
of stuff flying out.

00:03:03.420 --> 00:03:07.330
Whereas the electron and muon
machines may be more precision

00:03:07.330 --> 00:03:08.620
machines, is that?

00:03:08.620 --> 00:03:10.800
Another analogy, I don't
know if it's helpful,

00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:14.180
is that these very high
energy proton-proton machines,

00:03:14.180 --> 00:03:17.977
they're instruments which give
you a very broad field of view.

00:03:17.977 --> 00:03:20.310
So there's a lot going on,
and you have a big landscape,

00:03:20.310 --> 00:03:21.900
and you get a look
at the landscape.

00:03:21.900 --> 00:03:23.649
And then when you've
realized that there's

00:03:23.649 --> 00:03:26.370
a mountain in the distance
in the landscape, a Higgs

00:03:26.370 --> 00:03:28.060
boson for example,
you want to home

00:03:28.060 --> 00:03:29.880
in with a precision microscope.

00:03:29.880 --> 00:03:33.060
And that's where an electron
positron machine is exactly

00:03:33.060 --> 00:03:36.560
the instrument you want to make
Higgs bosons and nothing else.

00:03:36.560 --> 00:03:37.740
Could I just-- could I make?

00:03:37.740 --> 00:03:38.910
Yes, go ahead.

00:03:38.910 --> 00:03:40.760
So this is absolutely
correct, of course.

00:03:40.760 --> 00:03:43.530
Just two points to
pick up at the end.

00:03:43.530 --> 00:03:45.730
So once you've
scanned the landscape,

00:03:45.730 --> 00:03:48.450
it can be that the nature
that you're looking at

00:03:48.450 --> 00:03:53.010
has a particle in it which has
a quantum number of an electron

00:03:53.010 --> 00:03:54.890
as well as a quantum
number of a quark.

00:03:54.890 --> 00:03:57.220
