00:08:31.170 --> 00:08:37.230
So the tau is heavier,
1.7 GeV or so,

00:08:37.230 --> 00:08:41.080
compared to the muon
which has 106 MeV.

00:08:41.080 --> 00:08:46.290
So it's an order of
magnitude or more different.

00:08:46.290 --> 00:08:50.550
The rate of decay is going
at some power of the mass.

00:08:50.550 --> 00:08:55.500
So the lifetime of a tau is way
smaller than it is of a muon.

00:08:55.500 --> 00:08:58.550
And then because it's heavy it's
also more difficult to produce.

00:08:58.550 --> 00:09:00.850
So you get a lower rate
when you produce them,

00:09:00.850 --> 00:09:03.250
and they decay
more quickly, which

00:09:03.250 --> 00:09:06.200
means that the intensity of
the beam decays more quickly.

00:09:06.200 --> 00:09:09.450
So much, much harder.

00:09:09.450 --> 00:09:12.550
There's one more disad--
so the advantages

00:09:12.550 --> 00:09:14.800
you would get in the synchrotron
radiation all of that

00:09:14.800 --> 00:09:17.340
would be better because
they are heavier.

00:09:17.340 --> 00:09:20.160
