00:10:04.450 --> 00:10:10.780
Not problems, but-- one is-- so
the way that's been done so far

00:10:10.780 --> 00:10:14.970
is to drive this, to create a
wave that the charged particles

00:10:14.970 --> 00:10:17.671
can surf on inside the plasma.

00:10:17.671 --> 00:10:19.170
And to do that you
need to, sort of,

00:10:19.170 --> 00:10:21.080
send something
through the plasma

00:10:21.080 --> 00:10:22.560
to create a wave in its wake.

00:10:22.560 --> 00:10:24.030
That's why it's
called a wakefield,

00:10:24.030 --> 00:10:25.927
it's traveling
behind the driver.

00:10:25.927 --> 00:10:27.510
And so one of the
most successful ways

00:10:27.510 --> 00:10:29.680
that that's been done so
far is using a laser pulse

00:10:29.680 --> 00:10:30.480
to drive it.

00:10:30.480 --> 00:10:33.066
Now, these relativistic
particles all

00:10:33.066 --> 00:10:34.690
travel at basically
the speed of light.

00:10:34.690 --> 00:10:38.140
So it's 99.9999% of
the speed of light.

00:10:38.140 --> 00:10:41.540
The problem with
a laser is as soon

00:10:41.540 --> 00:10:44.404
as you put a light
which travels in vacuum

00:10:44.404 --> 00:10:46.820
at the speed of light, as soon
as you put it into a medium

00:10:46.820 --> 00:10:49.160
it travels a little bit slower
than the speed of light.

00:10:49.160 --> 00:10:51.850
And so when I do that in a
laser plasma accelerator,

00:10:51.850 --> 00:10:55.240
my driver is traveling a
little bit slower, maybe

00:10:55.240 --> 00:10:57.320
99.9% of the speed of light.

00:10:57.320 --> 00:10:58.230
So pretty close.

00:10:58.230 --> 00:11:03.690
But that difference
between 99.9% 99.99999%

00:11:03.690 --> 00:11:07.330
is enough that the electrons
are actually traveling faster

00:11:07.330 --> 00:11:10.270
than the wave which goes at the
same speed as the laser pulse.

00:11:10.270 --> 00:11:12.950
And so just like a
surfer on a water wave

00:11:12.950 --> 00:11:15.934
starts at the top of the wave
and ends up at the bottom,

00:11:15.934 --> 00:11:17.350
and once he's got
to the bottom he

00:11:17.350 --> 00:11:19.920
can't gain any
more energy, that's

00:11:19.920 --> 00:11:22.790
exactly what happens in a
laser driven plasma wave.

00:11:22.790 --> 00:11:24.730
So we start at the
top of the potential

00:11:24.730 --> 00:11:26.600
and we really drift down it.

00:11:26.600 --> 00:11:31.420
And once we get to that point,
we can't get any more energy.

00:11:31.420 --> 00:11:33.910
And so the maximum
energy that people

00:11:33.910 --> 00:11:36.920
are getting per in a single
stage of acceleration

00:11:36.920 --> 00:11:38.920
is limited by that process.

00:11:38.920 --> 00:11:42.590
So that's why even though it's
10,000 megavolts per meter,

00:11:42.590 --> 00:11:47.900
the limit is only 4 GeV in
less than 10 centimeters.

00:11:47.900 --> 00:11:50.050
There are some ways
around this, there

00:11:50.050 --> 00:11:53.820
are some really key
ways around this.

00:11:53.820 --> 00:11:57.690
One of the most obvious ones
is you just build another one.

00:11:57.690 --> 00:12:00.680
OK, so you got to 4
GeV in 10 centimeters.

00:12:00.680 --> 00:12:02.561
Somehow you have
another laser pulse,

00:12:02.561 --> 00:12:04.060
and you have another
10 centimeters,

00:12:04.060 --> 00:12:06.520
and you get up to 8 GeV,
and you keep doing that.

00:12:06.520 --> 00:12:08.644
So you can do that, and
you can look at the numbers

00:12:08.644 --> 00:12:11.550
and still, as long as you
don't have too much space

00:12:11.550 --> 00:12:14.910
in between these modules, then
your average accelerating rate

00:12:14.910 --> 00:12:19.490
is still much better than
the conventional ones.

00:12:19.490 --> 00:12:22.470
There are many issues with
that, many technical problems

00:12:22.470 --> 00:12:24.420
with that as well.

00:12:24.420 --> 00:12:28.090
Another way of doing this,
and this is quite cool,

00:12:28.090 --> 00:12:31.830
I mentioned that we use lasers
to drive the plasma wave.

00:12:31.830 --> 00:12:34.330
But the problem with a laser
is it travels a little bit less

00:12:34.330 --> 00:12:35.600
than the speed of light.

00:12:35.600 --> 00:12:38.100
But a charged particle beam
at a high enough energy

00:12:38.100 --> 00:12:39.640
is traveling at
the speed of light.

00:12:39.640 --> 00:12:41.499
And actually as a
charged particle beam,

00:12:41.499 --> 00:12:43.540
if it's intense enough,
travels through a plasma,

00:12:43.540 --> 00:12:46.480
it also drives this
wave, this plasma wave,

00:12:46.480 --> 00:12:47.980
that will accelerate it.

00:12:47.980 --> 00:12:49.480
And some very
successful experiments

00:12:49.480 --> 00:12:52.630
have been done on SLAC
over the last 10 years

00:12:52.630 --> 00:12:55.855
or so where they've used the
electron beam, and the positron

00:12:55.855 --> 00:12:57.230
beam for some of
the experiments,

00:12:57.230 --> 00:13:01.259
to drive a plasma
wave and accelerate

00:13:01.259 --> 00:13:02.300
some particles from that.

00:13:02.300 --> 00:13:03.990
And they've been doing
some great stuff.

00:13:03.990 --> 00:13:05.760
One of the, sort of,
key headline results

00:13:05.760 --> 00:13:07.370
happened a good
few years ago which

00:13:07.370 --> 00:13:11.050
was where they took the--
before SLAC was turned

00:13:11.050 --> 00:13:15.970
into an x-ray machine-- they
took the 40 GeV electron beam,

00:13:15.970 --> 00:13:19.770
so it's gone all, it's got taken
two miles, it's got to 40 GeV,

00:13:19.770 --> 00:13:23.430
then they put it into
a meter long plasma.

00:13:23.430 --> 00:13:25.350
That beam drove a plasma wave.

00:13:25.350 --> 00:13:28.130
Most of that beam slowed down
because it's energy was lost

00:13:28.130 --> 00:13:29.430
into driving the plasma wave.

00:13:29.430 --> 00:13:32.894
But right at the back
of the plasma wave,

00:13:32.894 --> 00:13:35.060
the back of the beam was
sitting in the accelerating

00:13:35.060 --> 00:13:37.420
part of the plasma wave,
and it doubled in energy

00:13:37.420 --> 00:13:39.350
in a plasma that was
just a meter long.

00:13:39.350 --> 00:13:43.270
So it took-- so really a few,
it wasn't a nice quality beam,

00:13:43.270 --> 00:13:45.230
but it really demonstrated
that these plasma

00:13:45.230 --> 00:13:46.640
waves have a huge potential.

00:13:46.640 --> 00:13:48.826
So two miles to
get up to 40 GeV,

00:13:48.826 --> 00:13:51.700
and another meter
to get up to 80 GeV.

00:13:51.700 --> 00:13:56.740
And so I think, I would say,
I'm a laser wakefield guy,

00:13:56.740 --> 00:13:58.890
