00:34:46.610 --> 00:34:47.449
is bottoms up.

00:34:47.449 --> 00:34:49.530
People have good ideas.

00:34:49.530 --> 00:34:52.170
They try and sell those
ideas to their colleagues.

00:34:52.170 --> 00:34:55.190
You try and gather a team of
people to pursue these ideas.

00:34:55.190 --> 00:34:57.160
You ask your funding
agency for some money

00:34:57.160 --> 00:35:00.410
to support some R&amp;D to
do experiments and push

00:35:00.410 --> 00:35:01.740
technology, and so on.

00:35:01.740 --> 00:35:05.450
If ideas look promising, bigger
international collaborations

00:35:05.450 --> 00:35:06.080
form.

00:35:06.080 --> 00:35:09.800
The one that I'm
privileged to lead

00:35:09.800 --> 00:35:11.980
has been going for
about 15 years now.

00:35:11.980 --> 00:35:15.250
We have 50 institutes from
around the world because people

00:35:15.250 --> 00:35:18.760
think, people believe that this
is a technology that really

00:35:18.760 --> 00:35:20.670
is very promising
and it's worth them

00:35:20.670 --> 00:35:23.010
dedicating their
scientific lives

00:35:23.010 --> 00:35:24.420
to trying to make it work.

00:35:24.420 --> 00:35:28.770
And we've been able to achieve
funding for the project.

00:35:28.770 --> 00:35:30.400
But, of course,
at some point you

00:35:30.400 --> 00:35:33.170
have to move from
an R&amp;D enterprise

00:35:33.170 --> 00:35:37.580
to a real major facility that
is actually going to be built.

00:35:37.580 --> 00:35:42.400
And those are, these days,
billion pound, dollar,

00:35:42.400 --> 00:35:44.690
euro class facilities.

00:35:44.690 --> 00:35:47.160
And that's where it becomes
a little bit more exciting,

00:35:47.160 --> 00:35:48.730
because then the
world, of course,

00:35:48.730 --> 00:35:53.330
cannot possibly afford to have--
if the money were unlimited,

00:35:53.330 --> 00:35:55.650
we'd have all of these things.

00:35:55.650 --> 00:35:58.720
We'd have electron positron,
proton proton, muons,

00:35:58.720 --> 00:36:01.420
and a super duper plasma
wakefield accelerator.

00:36:01.420 --> 00:36:04.340
These projects are now
of a sufficient scale

00:36:04.340 --> 00:36:08.350
of technical complexity
and cost that it's

00:36:08.350 --> 00:36:10.120
very difficult to
have more than one

00:36:10.120 --> 00:36:12.550
or two running in the world.

00:36:12.550 --> 00:36:15.770
And people come together
globally to collaborate,

00:36:15.770 --> 00:36:17.680
to try to realize and
bring the resources

00:36:17.680 --> 00:36:20.620
together to realize
multi-billion projects.

00:36:20.620 --> 00:36:23.430
And they get spread out
over a long time scale.

00:36:23.430 --> 00:36:25.050
That's why you saw
in Frank's slide,

00:36:25.050 --> 00:36:29.040
I think, 20 years gestation
period for the Large Hadron

00:36:29.040 --> 00:36:30.050
Collider.

00:36:30.050 --> 00:36:32.820
And, hence, you've got to
run the thing for 20 years

00:36:32.820 --> 00:36:36.070
in order to fully exploit
it, and get all of the data,

00:36:36.070 --> 00:36:38.912
and all the information to make
that investment worthwhile.

00:36:38.912 --> 00:36:41.120
So I think I'm straying from
the question now, Suzie.

00:36:41.120 --> 00:36:42.860
Maybe I'll let somebody
else have a go.

00:36:42.860 --> 00:36:44.990
But it's fundamentally
bottoms up.

00:36:44.990 --> 00:36:46.950
And at some level you've
got to get serious,

00:36:46.950 --> 00:36:48.990
and you've got to get
quite a lot of money.

00:36:48.990 --> 00:36:52.110
And that's when politics, of
course, and global politics

00:36:52.110 --> 00:36:54.010
starts to enter
into the picture.

00:36:54.010 --> 00:36:56.720
So maybe we can continue
on that, actually,

00:36:56.720 --> 00:36:59.680
about the politics and the
international community

00:36:59.680 --> 00:37:00.280
of science.

00:37:00.280 --> 00:37:04.260
There's been a lot of articles
and Information said about CERN

00:37:04.260 --> 00:37:07.084
bringing together people
who might traditionally not

00:37:07.084 --> 00:37:09.500
have worked together and how
that's had a positive effect.

00:37:09.500 --> 00:37:12.440
And I know you've all worked in
very international communities.

00:37:12.440 --> 00:37:15.840
So would any of you like
to comment on the, sort of,

00:37:15.840 --> 00:37:18.880
positive aspects of the very
international cooperation

00:37:18.880 --> 00:37:20.830
that happens in this field?

00:37:20.830 --> 00:37:23.850
Maybe Ken, would you
like to comment on that?

00:37:23.850 --> 00:37:26.200
Or disagree with the statement?

00:37:26.200 --> 00:37:27.700
I don't disagree
with the statement.

00:37:27.700 --> 00:37:31.720
So I think CERN is a very,
very special organization.

00:37:31.720 --> 00:37:37.370
So it created in the '50s
when, obviously, Europe

00:37:37.370 --> 00:37:39.820
was recovering after the war.

00:37:39.820 --> 00:37:41.600
It's an international
treaty organization,

00:37:41.600 --> 00:37:43.890
that's very special, I think.

00:37:43.890 --> 00:37:49.130
To create the conditions in
which such a treaty could

00:37:49.130 --> 00:37:54.430
be negotiated and signed you
would need special conditions.

00:37:54.430 --> 00:37:55.950
And they existed.

00:37:55.950 --> 00:37:58.170
The value of that is
seen across the world,

00:37:58.170 --> 00:38:04.520
and CERN continues to
attract more countries.

00:38:04.520 --> 00:38:07.980
And there's a negotiation period
there because they have to,

00:38:07.980 --> 00:38:11.670
the treaty has to be agreed
by all the other members,

00:38:11.670 --> 00:38:15.160
and there are, you have to
contribute to the budget,

00:38:15.160 --> 00:38:17.660
and that's an international
treaty obligation

00:38:17.660 --> 00:38:18.860
once you're a member.

00:38:18.860 --> 00:38:23.460
So that brings in
inertia, because clearly

00:38:23.460 --> 00:38:26.480
to get all the governments
to agree to a treaty change

00:38:26.480 --> 00:38:27.490
takes time.

00:38:27.490 --> 00:38:28.900
But it's robust.

00:38:28.900 --> 00:38:30.640
Because with the
international treaty

00:38:30.640 --> 00:38:34.195
comes some kind of
collective responsibility

00:38:34.195 --> 00:38:36.070
of all those governments
that have signed it.

00:38:36.070 --> 00:38:40.820
And that's why CERN is as
successful and as stable

00:38:40.820 --> 00:38:41.766
as it is.

00:38:41.766 --> 00:38:45.310
It is driven by science,
wants the best science

00:38:45.310 --> 00:38:46.480
that can be done.

00:38:46.480 --> 00:38:50.380
And that, actually, I think is
a unique combination of things.

00:38:50.380 --> 00:38:53.330
The international
treaty organization

00:38:53.330 --> 00:38:57.620
which is there to deliver
fundamental science.

00:38:57.620 --> 00:39:02.850
That's a jewel in our collective
crown and we should protect it.

00:39:02.850 --> 00:39:05.530
So, basically I agree.

00:39:05.530 --> 00:39:06.530
Maybe I can add to that.

00:39:06.530 --> 00:39:09.600
I think that especially
British accelerators have made

00:39:09.600 --> 00:39:11.570
enormous contributions to CERN.

00:39:11.570 --> 00:39:15.820
John Adams commissioned the PS,
and he built the SPS collider.

00:39:15.820 --> 00:39:18.210
And then Lyn Evans
built the LHC.

00:39:18.210 --> 00:39:20.610
So, actually Britain
has a proud history in--

00:39:20.610 --> 00:39:24.040
Yeah, it was Mike Lamont is
leading the LHC operation.

00:39:24.040 --> 00:39:27.320
It's just a wonderful,
wonderful collaboration

00:39:27.320 --> 00:39:30.440
between the different nations
of Europe and around the world.

00:39:30.440 --> 00:39:33.220
And it's working very
well, the system.

00:39:33.220 --> 00:39:36.570
I think it's kind of a model
for successful international

00:39:36.570 --> 00:39:37.450
cooperation.

00:39:37.450 --> 00:39:41.110
Many people complain about
ITER and the fusion development

00:39:41.110 --> 00:39:43.390
because it maybe looks
less successful and not so

00:39:43.390 --> 00:39:43.900
efficient.

00:39:43.900 --> 00:39:46.150
But the CERN model
is quite efficient.

00:39:46.150 --> 00:39:49.000
Of course, we do live in
interesting times with regard

00:39:49.000 --> 00:39:52.640
to European treaty organization.

00:39:52.640 --> 00:39:56.710
But it is worth pointing out
that CERN predates the European

00:39:56.710 --> 00:39:58.366
Union by three years.

00:39:58.366 --> 00:40:00.490
And it's a completely
separate International treaty

00:40:00.490 --> 00:40:02.250
organization.

00:40:02.250 --> 00:40:04.050
And so we're often
asked, you know,

00:40:04.050 --> 00:40:07.670
what does Brexit mean for the
UK's involvement with CERN.

00:40:07.670 --> 00:40:11.220
Well, hopefully, to the extent
that Her Majesty's government

00:40:11.220 --> 00:40:12.950
continues to pay
our subscription

00:40:12.950 --> 00:40:15.340
to the international
organization,

00:40:15.340 --> 00:40:17.810
we will continue to be
full members of CERN.

00:40:17.810 --> 00:40:19.560
And as Frank has
very generously said,

00:40:19.560 --> 00:40:23.920
play a very important role
in this greater entity.

00:40:23.920 --> 00:40:25.920
So we've only got a
couple of minutes left.

00:40:25.920 --> 00:40:27.461
So I'm going to ask
if there is maybe

00:40:27.461 --> 00:40:30.990
one more question from the
audience before I wind up.

00:40:30.990 --> 00:40:34.020
Is there one more going?

00:40:34.020 --> 00:40:36.370
There's one right up the
back in the middle, I think.

00:40:36.370 --> 00:40:38.490
If I can, you're
just below a light,

00:40:38.490 --> 00:40:40.186
so that was very
difficult to see.

00:40:47.760 --> 00:40:48.730
There we go.

00:40:48.730 --> 00:40:53.310
Hello there, I was wondering,
you know for electron colliders

00:40:53.310 --> 00:40:55.760
you have the electron
and positron colliders.

00:40:55.760 --> 00:41:00.730
Is there any muon-antigluon
or tau-antiatu colliders

00:41:00.730 --> 00:41:01.840
that exist?

00:41:01.840 --> 00:41:07.726
And if there are, is it perhaps
influential in discovery

00:41:07.726 --> 00:41:12.510
for a new powerful
collider, for instance?

00:41:12.510 --> 00:41:14.360
So, do any muon colliders exist?

00:41:14.360 --> 00:41:19.050
No they don't.

00:41:19.050 --> 00:41:21.530
So people have made muon
beams, many, many muon

00:41:21.530 --> 00:41:24.920
beams around the world, a muon
beam at Rutherford Appleton

00:41:24.920 --> 00:41:27.120
Laboratory, for example.

00:41:27.120 --> 00:41:30.400
The difficulty is making
the beams intense enough.

00:41:30.400 --> 00:41:35.450
So I had a slide which was
intense cold muon beams, cold

00:41:35.450 --> 00:41:39.640
is a jargon for this small beam.

00:41:39.640 --> 00:41:43.200
So if you want to get
collisions at a large rate,

00:41:43.200 --> 00:41:46.950
you have to have either an
enormous number of particles,

00:41:46.950 --> 00:41:49.020
or you bring them into
a tiny, tiny spot.

00:41:49.020 --> 00:41:53.570
So both ILC, CLIC, FCC,
they all make the particles

00:41:53.570 --> 00:41:55.420
into a tiny, tiny spot.

00:41:55.420 --> 00:41:56.880
So to do the
neutrino science, you

00:41:56.880 --> 00:41:59.110
need a cucumber of particles.

00:41:59.110 --> 00:42:01.030
If you want a muon
collider, you've

00:42:01.030 --> 00:42:04.920
got to have something less
than the thickness of a hair.

00:42:04.920 --> 00:42:07.380
That's the size of the
beam that has to collide.

00:42:07.380 --> 00:42:09.050
So the difficulty
is that you have

00:42:09.050 --> 00:42:13.800
to reduce the size
of the beam such

00:42:13.800 --> 00:42:15.940
that you can get
enough collisions.

00:42:15.940 --> 00:42:18.220
And that's what this
cooling business is about

00:42:18.220 --> 00:42:21.000
that we're building the
experiment at Rutherford Lab.

00:42:21.000 --> 00:42:23.630
And we need to demonstrate
that technology,

00:42:23.630 --> 00:42:26.350
and then we can discuss
making the muon collider.

00:42:26.350 --> 00:42:29.150
OK, so I have one final
question for each of you

00:42:29.150 --> 00:42:32.597
just before we leave
which is for the younger

00:42:32.597 --> 00:42:34.430
people in the audience
tonight, or for those

00:42:34.430 --> 00:42:36.910
who are particularly
interested in this field,

00:42:36.910 --> 00:42:38.370
do you have any
advice for people

00:42:38.370 --> 00:42:40.230
who might be
interested in working

00:42:40.230 --> 00:42:45.510
on these future machines that
might come along in very soon,

00:42:45.510 --> 00:42:48.770
or 10, 20 years time,
40, 50 years time?

00:42:48.770 --> 00:42:50.850
Any sage words of
advice before we go?

00:42:50.850 --> 00:42:53.880
I'm going to start on this end.

00:42:53.880 --> 00:42:57.500
Well, I'm sorry, the
trite answer in the UK

00:42:57.500 --> 00:43:01.065
is, of course, that you've
got to do physics at a level.

00:43:01.065 --> 00:43:04.720
And especially if you are a
female member of the audience,

00:43:04.720 --> 00:43:07.200
we desperately want you
to do physics at a level.

00:43:07.200 --> 00:43:10.410
And I can see there's a
budding accelerator physicist

00:43:10.410 --> 00:43:12.250
on the front row here.

00:43:12.250 --> 00:43:13.980
Yeah, physics at a level.

00:43:13.980 --> 00:43:16.280
Go and do your physics degree.

00:43:16.280 --> 00:43:19.260
Go and get a summer intern
at CERN, for example,

00:43:19.260 --> 00:43:23.150
and go and spend eight or
10 weeks during your summer

00:43:23.150 --> 00:43:26.470
vacation working on
a project at CERN.

00:43:26.470 --> 00:43:27.180
Get excitement.

00:43:27.180 --> 00:43:27.920
Get fired up.

00:43:27.920 --> 00:43:33.360
And then come to the John Adams
Institute and do your PhD.

00:43:33.360 --> 00:43:35.180
Frank, anything to add to that?

00:43:35.180 --> 00:43:39.340
Yeah, I'm doing accelerator
physics in 27 years, or so.

00:43:39.340 --> 00:43:41.660
I did my diplomacies,
and then PhD,

00:43:41.660 --> 00:43:44.170
and I already studied with
accelerators and colliders.

00:43:44.170 --> 00:43:46.670
And I enjoyed very much that
you can do all kinds of things.

00:43:46.670 --> 00:43:49.430
You can be in the control
room playing with the beam,

00:43:49.430 --> 00:43:50.760
and optimizing the operation.

00:43:50.760 --> 00:43:51.620
Can I just check,
do you actually

00:43:51.620 --> 00:43:52.578
get to control the LHC?

00:43:52.578 --> 00:43:54.336
Is that part of your job?

00:43:54.336 --> 00:43:55.460
Not at the moment any more.

00:43:55.460 --> 00:43:56.460
But you have?

00:43:56.460 --> 00:43:58.020
In the past, yes.

00:43:58.020 --> 00:43:59.170
How cool is that?

00:43:59.170 --> 00:44:00.310
Sorry, I get jealous.

00:44:00.310 --> 00:44:03.200
For some experiments we
can control the LHC, yes.

00:44:06.810 --> 00:44:08.050
So it's fun career?

00:44:08.050 --> 00:44:09.810
Yeah, you can do
computer simulations.

00:44:09.810 --> 00:44:10.930
I do a lot of
computer simulations.

00:44:10.930 --> 00:44:12.460
You can do analytical
calculations

00:44:12.460 --> 00:44:14.610
and you are more or
less free to choose.

00:44:14.610 --> 00:44:17.850
And I like the combination,
it never gets boring.

00:44:17.850 --> 00:44:19.849
I can spend some day
in the control room

00:44:19.849 --> 00:44:21.640
with the operators, I
can spend another day

00:44:21.640 --> 00:44:24.680
in my office doing simulations,
or you can have meetings,

00:44:24.680 --> 00:44:25.450
or whatever.

00:44:25.450 --> 00:44:27.777
But you can do many
different things.

00:44:27.777 --> 00:44:30.110
You are more flexible than
many other fields of physics,

00:44:30.110 --> 00:44:31.070
I think.

00:44:31.070 --> 00:44:34.450
And we need a lot, we need
more accelerator physicists.

00:44:34.450 --> 00:44:37.810
We have never enough applicants
for doctoral students,

00:44:37.810 --> 00:44:39.230
or for post docs.

00:44:39.230 --> 00:44:41.200
We never find candidates.

00:44:41.200 --> 00:44:44.160
We have many more
posts than applicants.

00:44:44.160 --> 00:44:44.990
So anybody--

00:44:44.990 --> 00:44:47.380
OK, if you want a job
at CERN, now you know.

00:44:47.380 --> 00:44:49.960
I must say, yeah,
it's very difficult.

00:44:49.960 --> 00:44:50.940
They're oversubscribed.

00:44:50.940 --> 00:44:52.731
Last year the post docs
were oversubscribed

00:44:52.731 --> 00:44:54.120
by a factor of 10, or so.

00:44:54.120 --> 00:44:56.141
10 different groups asked
for the same candidate

00:44:56.141 --> 00:44:57.640
because there are
so few candidates.

00:44:57.640 --> 00:45:01.070
So that's why FCC is not faster,
because we cannot get all

00:45:01.070 --> 00:45:02.290
the post docs that we need.

00:45:02.290 --> 00:45:04.200
So we need smart people.

00:45:04.200 --> 00:45:08.974
And then maybe also, maybe the
time scale is a bit worrying.

00:45:08.974 --> 00:45:11.140
You don't want to wait 20
years for the next machine

00:45:11.140 --> 00:45:11.430
accelerator.

00:45:11.430 --> 00:45:13.170
But I enjoyed very
much, I can always

00:45:13.170 --> 00:45:16.090
work on an operating machine,
work on the next generation,

00:45:16.090 --> 00:45:18.780
and also look at the
generation beyond the next.

00:45:18.780 --> 00:45:19.890
So I like this very much.

00:45:19.890 --> 00:45:22.939
And you can learn, you always
learn from the existing machine

00:45:22.939 --> 00:45:25.230
what to improve and what to
do better for the next one.

00:45:25.230 --> 00:45:26.313
Long term, long term view.

00:45:26.313 --> 00:45:28.900
You can do the things
at the same time.

00:45:28.900 --> 00:45:31.700
Yeah, that's a good
point, actually.

00:45:31.700 --> 00:45:33.140
Anything to add over this side?

00:45:33.140 --> 00:45:34.725
I might just have
one thing, sorry.

00:45:34.725 --> 00:45:35.350
Yeah, go ahead.

00:45:35.350 --> 00:45:37.808
Which is that, so one of the
good things about doing plasma

00:45:37.808 --> 00:45:39.990
based acceleration certainly
is, as a PhD student,

00:45:39.990 --> 00:45:42.460
is the time scale of the
way things are moving

00:45:42.460 --> 00:45:45.790
is much faster and the
experiments are much smaller.

00:45:45.790 --> 00:45:49.020
So you almost get
to own a large part

00:45:49.020 --> 00:45:50.370
of the project all of your own.

00:45:50.370 --> 00:45:52.470
Whereas if you get involved
in very big machines

00:45:52.470 --> 00:45:55.580
you can be very, very focused on
a really important part that's

00:45:55.580 --> 00:45:58.475
making a big contribution
to something very important,

00:45:58.475 --> 00:45:59.850
but it can be kept
very detailed.

00:45:59.850 --> 00:46:02.400
Whereas I think when you're
doing the plasma based stuff

00:46:02.400 --> 00:46:05.010
it's quite fun because
you do everything

00:46:05.010 --> 00:46:08.530
from building the machine, to
designing it with simulations,

00:46:08.530 --> 00:46:10.564
to doing all of the
data analysis and stuff

00:46:10.564 --> 00:46:11.230
all on your own.

00:46:11.230 --> 00:46:14.000
So it's kind of fun
like that as well.

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:17.190
And not to be left out,
Ken, anything to add?

00:46:17.190 --> 00:46:24.102
So I've been thinking, so
this it's-- I'm going to say

00:46:24.102 --> 00:46:26.310
something which is personal,
which I never really do.

00:46:26.310 --> 00:46:28.350
I have two daughters,
one of whom

00:46:28.350 --> 00:46:31.390
is genuinely considering
particle physics.

00:46:31.390 --> 00:46:33.400
And therefore this is
a real question for me

00:46:33.400 --> 00:46:35.030
not an academic question.

00:46:35.030 --> 00:46:37.300
And what I say to her
is follow your heart.

00:46:37.300 --> 00:46:39.184
And I've had a
great time, right,

00:46:39.184 --> 00:46:40.850
I've never done a
day's work in my life.

00:46:40.850 --> 00:46:45.010
What I do beats working
for a living, really great.

00:46:45.010 --> 00:46:49.270
If she falls in love with
another area, follow that.

00:46:49.270 --> 00:46:51.790
Because that's what
will make you work.

00:46:51.790 --> 00:46:55.220
Particle physics, accelerator
science is fantastic.

00:46:55.220 --> 00:46:58.927
If you love something
else, do that.

00:46:58.927 --> 00:47:00.510
